1 (1) A sentence of imprisonment for a felony shall be an indeterminate sentence, the
2 maximum of which shall be fixed within the limits provided by subsection (2) of
3 this section, and subject to modification by the trial judge pursuant to KRS 532.070.
4 (2) Unless otherwise provided by law, the authorized maximum terms of imprisonment
5 for felonies are:
6 (a) For a Class A felony, not less than twenty (20) years nor more than fifty (50)
7 years, or life imprisonment;
8 (b) For a Class B felony, not less than ten (10) years nor more than twenty (20)
9 years;
10 (c) For a Class C felony, not less than five (5) years nor more than ten (10) years;
11 and
12 (d) For a Class D felony, not less than one (1) year nor more than five (5) years.
13 (3) For any felony specified in KRS Chapter 510, felony attempt to commit a felony
14 offense specified in KRS Chapter 510, or KRS 529.100, 529.110, 530.020,
15 530.064(1)(a), or 531.310 to 531.370[, 531.320, 531.335, or 531.340], the sentence
16 shall include an additional five (5) year period of postincarceration supervision
17 which shall be added to the maximum sentence rendered for the offense. During
18 this period of postincarceration supervision, if a defendant violates the provisions of
19 postincarceration supervision, the defendant may be reincarcerated for:
20 (a) The remaining period of his or her initial sentence, if any is remaining; and
21 (b) The entire period of postincarceration supervision, or if the initial sentence
22 has been served, for the remaining period of postincarceration supervision.
23 (4) In addition to the penalties provided in this section, for any person subject to a
24 period of postincarceration supervision pursuant to KRS 532.400 his or her
25 sentence shall include an additional one (1) year period of postincarceration
26 supervision following release from incarceration upon expiration of sentence if the
27 offender is not otherwise subject to another form of postincarceration supervision.
